  "text": "In the Grafana datasource plugin (sg-evals/grafana--26d36ec), the HTTP client for Loki queries is the `LokiAPI` struct defined in pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go (lines 29-34). This struct wraps an `*http.Client` and is responsible for executing HTTP requests to the Loki backend. The struct contains:\n- client: *http.Client (the actual HTTP client for making requests)\n- url: string (the Loki datasource URL)\n- log: log.Logger (for logging)\n- tracer: trace.Tracer (for distributed tracing)\n\nThe LokiAPI is instantiated via the newLokiAPI() function (lines 42-44 in api.go) and used by methods like DataQuery() and RawQuery() to execute queries against the Loki API endpoints.\n\nFor parsing incoming HTTP instant query requests on the Grafana side, the main entry point is the `QueryData` method (pkg/tsdb/loki/loki.go, lines 182-196), which implements the backend.QueryDataHandler interface. This delegates to the internal `queryData()` function (lines 198-242) which calls `parseQuery()` (pkg/tsdb/loki/parse_query.go, lines 128-199).\n\nThe `parseQuery()` function is the key parser that:\n1. Iterates through incoming query requests from the Grafana frontend\n2. Unmarshals JSON query models via parseQueryModel()\n3. Parses query type (instant/range) via parseQueryType()\n4. Parses query direction (backward/forward) via parseDirection()\n5. Parses supporting query type via parseSupportingQueryType()\n6. Interpolates template variables in the LogQL expression\n7. Returns an array of lokiQuery structs containing the parsed parameters\n\nThese parsed queries are then passed to makeDataRequest() (api.go, lines 46-109) which constructs the HTTP GET request to send to the Loki backend. For instant queries specifically, makeDataRequest() constructs requests to the /loki/api/v1/query endpoint with parameters: query (LogQL expression), time (Unix nanosecond timestamp), direction, and limit (if specified).\n\nThe full chain flows: HTTP request → QueryData handler → parseQuery parser → lokiQuery objects → makeDataRequest builder → LokiAPI.DataQuery executor → http.Client.Do()"
}

